## Differences Between Unity and enterprise .NET
- Unity works differently with C#. Enterprise .NET has another pipeline and there is no loop functionality.
- In Unity there is only one game taking place at a time, where monobehaviour carries state across frames. in .NET the API processes numerous requests per second concurrently.

## Pipelines
- CLR (CommonLenguageRuntime) = .NET Runtime
- IL (Intermediate Lenguage) || CIL (Common Intermediate Lenguage) = CPU-agnostic bytecode && lives inside a .dll file with metadata, describing every type and method.
- JIT (Just In Time) = happens at runtime. Assemblies are loaded on demand.
- CPU and platform-agnostic bytecode means a low-level compiled format that is not tied to any specific kind of processor arquitecture. That means that its not executed by hardware but by an intermedary software layer, like a virtual machine.
- The result of compiling a .cs file is IL, not native machine code. 
- The CLR or .NET runtime JIT-compiles the IL to native machine code the first time each method is called.The CPU then executes. The next calls come from the cached native version.

## Assemblies
- aasembly = .dll file || .exe file
- Assemblies are deployed to a server, have their own version number and are controlled by project preferences to determined which assemblies communicate with each other nad which don't.
- While working with numerous specific layers in a project, the .Domain must not reference any other layer to garantee the stability of the site

## Namespaces
- Namespace = a logical container for types with no runtime significance. It's used for organisation and collision prevention purposes.
- It mirrors the folder path.

## Value Types vs Reference Types
- Value Types = int, long, float, double, bool, char, byte, decimal, DtaTime, Guid, all structs, all enums.
- Value types are stored directly where they are declared. When a Value type is assigned, you get an independent copy.
- Reference Types = all classes, all interfaces, arrays, delegates, strings.
- Reference Types store a reference (a memory adress) to an object that lives on the manageed heap. That means that there is an abstract object, which can be referenced by more then one variables, making a copys with direct access to the subjective object.
- Reference Types can be null. <Nullable>enable</Nullable> // in .csproj to use ?, ?. and ??

## Strings
- Strings is a reference type, but behaves like a value type because is immutable. It is possible only to add more strings to an already existing string and not to modify it.

## Access Modifiers
- While in Unity one tends to use often and freely public and private, in .NET the access modifiers are treated more as a formal architecture enforcement.

**Modifier - Accessible from**
public - Anywhere
private - only within the declaring type
protected - declaring type and all subclasses
internal - only within the same assembly
protected internal - same assembly or any subclassa anywhere
private protected - same assembly and subclasses only

## Record Types
- Records give immutability and value equality by default. Properties are init only, can be mutated in an non-destructve way with with. 
- Two identical command are treated here identically.

## Static
- static members belong to the type, not to an instance. Are in the memory for the entire application lifetime.

**Why to use it with care?**
- static field is shared across all possible requests processed by the ASP.NET Core API.
- static dependencies cannot be mocked in tests.
- static state breaks dependency injection.

 **when to use it?**
- for pure utility methods with no state
- for constants

## var - inference, not dynamic
- var is a compile-time type inference.
- The compiler determines the type from the right-hand side at compile time.
- it is not dynamic.
- It can be used when the type is obvious from the right side. The explicit type can be used when it carries architectural meaning, when there is a necessity to make the destinction.



